lture and Civic Engagement\";s:11:\"description\";s:856:\"Henry Jenkins is the Provost\'s Professor of Communication, Journalism, and Cinematic Arts at the University of Southern California. He arrived at USC in Fall 2009 after spending the past decade as the Director of the MIT Comparative Media Studies Program and the Peter de Florez Professor of Humanities. He is the author and/or editor of twelve books on various aspects of media and popular culture. He was one of the first media scholars to chart the changing role of the audience in an environment of increasingly pervasive digital content, and he has been at the forefront of understanding the effects of participatory media on society, politics and culture. His research gives key insights to the success of social-networking Web sites, networked computer games, online fan communities and other advocacy organizations, and emerging news media outlets.\";s:3:\"url\";s:25:\"http://vimeo.com/16262538\";s:11:\"upload_date\";s:19:\"2010-10-27 19:39:14\";s:15:\"thumbnail_small\";s:49:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/992/928/99292898_100.jpg\";s:16:\"thumbnail_medium\";s:49:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/992/928/99292898_200.jpg\";s:15:\"thumbnail_large\";s:49:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/992/928/99292898_640.jpg\";s:9:\"user_name\";s:16:\"DML Research Hub\";s:8:\"user_url\";s:28:\"http://vimeo.com/user3914399\";s:19:\"user_portrait_small\";s:47:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ps/119/715/1197151_30.jpg\";s:20:\"user_portrait_medium\";s:47:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ps/119/715/1197151_75.jpg\";s:19:\"user_portrait_large\";s:48:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ps/119/715/1197151_100.jpg\";s:18:\"user_portrait_huge\";s:48:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ps/119/715/1197151_300.jpg\";s:21:\"stats_number_of_likes\";s:1:\"0\";s:21:\"stats_number_of_plays\";s:2:\"80\";s:24:\"stats_number_of_comments\";i:0;s:8:\"duration\";s:3:\"455\";s:5:\"width\";s:3:\"640\";s:6:\"height\";s:3:\"360\";s:4:\"tags\";s:261:\"Participatory Culture, Crowdsourcing, Digital Culture, Civic Engagement, Participatory Politics, Democracy, Popular Culture, Society, Harry Potter Alliance, Social Enterprise, Games, Interest-driven Learning, Internet Culture, Teachers 2.0, New Media Literacies\";}}',1301406726,1301403126,'',1),('vimeo::16289972','a:1:{i:0;a:21:{s:2:\"id\";s:8:\"16289972\";s:5:\"title\";s:102:\"Cultural Anthropologist Mimi Ito on Connected Learning, Children, and Digital Media in a Networked Age\";s:11:\"description\";s:750:\"Mimi Ito is a cultural anthropologist and expert in the field of digital media and learning, focusing on children and youth\'s changing relationships to media and communications. She is a Professor in Residence at the Department of Anthropology and the Department of Informatics at the University of California, Irvine, and serves as Research Director of the Digital Media and Learning Research Hub in the system-wide University of California Humanities Research Institute. She recently completed the Digital Youth Project, a landmark study supported by the MacArthur Foundation of the ways youth use new media. In September 2010, she was appointed as the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation Chair in Digital Media and Learning at UC Irvine.\";s:3:\"url\";s:25:\"http://vimeo.com/16289972\";s:11:\"upload_date\";s:19:\"2010-10-28 15:19:32\";s:15:\"thumbnail_small\";s:49:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/995/093/99509384_100.jpg\";s:16:\"thumbnail_medium\";s:49:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/995/093/99509384_200.jpg\";s:15:\"thumbnail_large\";s:49:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/995/093/99509384_640.jpg\";s:9:\"user_name\";s:16:\"DML Research Hub\";s:8:\"user_url\";s:28:\"http://vimeo.com/user3914399\";s:19:\"user_portrait_small\";s:47:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ps/119/715/1197151_30.jpg\";s:20:\"user_portrait_medium\";s:47:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ps/119/715/1197151_75.jpg\";s:19:\"user_portrait_large\";s:48:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ps/119/715/1197151_100.jpg\";s:18:\"user_portrait_huge\";s:48:\"http://b.vimeocdn.com/ps/119/715/1197151_300.jpg\"